  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/3267",
  "title": "Question: best practice when using infinite scrolling while the content is being modified",
  "body": "I was wondering what the best practice was supposed to be when I use infinite scrolling, and the content changes server-side while a user is navigating, which leads to duplicates in the results displayed to the user.\r\n\r\nSuppose I store news articles in Algolia and a user asks for the first 10 results (index 0 to 9) ordered by creation date (newest first).\r\nAfter the user obtains the first 10 results, a different user creates a new article.\r\nSince the article is new, it is inserted at index 0 in the ordered list of articles.\r\nTherefore, the article that was previously at index 9 is now moved to index 10.\r\nWhen the first user asks for the next page of results, he will obtain 10 results, index 10 to 19.\r\nThe user will see a duplicate, as the result he got at index 9 is also visible at index 10.\r\n\r\nThis is problematic for infinite scrolling, as the duplicates are visually right next to each other.\r\n\r\nTo stop this from happening, I use lodash\r\n`const uniqueHits = _.uniqBy(hits, 'objectID');`\r\nin the function I pass to connectInfiniteHits.\r\n\r\nIs this best practice? Should this be handled transparently by the connector instead?",
  "created_at": "2018-11-15T09:59:07Z",
